From: Florian Maurer <fmaurer@disroot.org>
Subject: [PATCH] arm64: smp: call rcutree_report_cpu_dead() in local_cpu_stop()

local_cpu_stop() (used by both panic_smp_self_stop() and the IPI_CPU_STOP
handler in do_handle_IPI()) clears the dying CPU from cpu_online_mask
and then parks the CPU in cpu_park_loop() without telling RCU. This is
the arm64 analog of the ARM ipi_cpu_stop() gap fixed in the previous
patch: RCU's qsmaskinitnext and ffmask bits for the stopped CPU remain
set while cpu_is_offline() returns true, which can lead to a long RCU
stall and a WARN in irq_work_queue_on() when force_qs_rnp() targets the
now-offline CPU.

arm64 already establishes this pattern in cpu_die_early(), which calls
rcutree_report_cpu_dead() after set_cpu_present(cpu, 0); apply the same
treatment to local_cpu_stop(). Place the call after local_daif_mask() so
IRQs are guaranteed masked when rcutree_report_cpu_dead()'s
lockdep_assert_irqs_disabled() runs (both panic_smp_self_stop() and the
IPI path enter with IRQs disabled, but local_daif_mask() makes the
invariant explicit).

NOTE: this arm64 sibling patch is by analogy with the ARM fix and has
not been runtime-tested on arm64 hardware. The bug is structurally
identical (verified against arch/arm64/kernel/smp.c in mainline), but a
real reproducer on arm64 would be useful before merge.

The crash-stop path ipi_cpu_crash_stop() has a similar gap when
CONFIG_HOTPLUG_CPU=n (when set, __cpu_try_die() handles RCU teardown
via the normal cpuhp machinery); that case is left for a separate
patch.

Signed-off-by: Florian Maurer <fmaurer@disroot.org>
---
 arch/arm64/kernel/smp.c | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

--- a/arch/arm64/kernel/smp.c
+++ b/arch/arm64/kernel/smp.c
@@ -866,6 +866,8 @@ static void __noreturn local_cpu_stop(un
 	set_cpu_online(cpu, false);

 	local_daif_mask();
+	rcutree_report_cpu_dead();
+
 	sdei_mask_local_cpu();
 	cpu_park_loop();
 }
